# Spatial-Frequency Interactive Fusion Network with Transformer-CNN for Smoke Segmentation (SFIFN)

## Overall

Overall framework of the proposed SFIFN. The model takes an input image and employs a Frequency Dual-Branch Encoder (with Transformer and CNN branches) to extract multi-scale features from both spatial and frequency domains. The Transformer branch captures long-range dependencies and diffusion patterns via FFE-Trans with EFCA and MS-FFN, while the CNN branch extracts local textures and edge details via FMLM with DEB and FMA. The Multi-level Joint Domain Fusion (MJDF) module aligns local and global contexts via frequency-domain cross-attention and smoke-aware axial attention. Finally, the Multi-scale Fusion Dual-domain Decoder (MFDD) progressively upsamples and integrates spatial and frequency information through gated fusion, deformable convolution, and frequency-enhanced upsampling. The Frequency Contrastive Loss (FCL) explicitly constrains smoke-background distribution differences in the frequency domain, forming cross-domain synergistic supervision with spatial-domain loss.

<p align="center">
  <img src="./figures/framework.png" alt="SFIFN Framework" width="90%">
</p>

> **Figure 1:** Overall framework of the proposed SFIFN.

## Prepare Data

We evaluate SFIFN on three smoke segmentation datasets:

- **USS** [[1]](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/10335563): A real-world smoke segmentation dataset containing 3,217 images with pixel-level annotations. The dataset is split into training and testing sets with a ratio of 8:2.

- **SYN70K** [[2]](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0925231219309378): A synthetic smoke dataset comprising 70,632 training images and 3,000 test images, including three test subsets (DS01, DS02, DS03).

- **SmokeSeg** [[3]](https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0031320325007097): A challenging real-world dataset focusing on small-scale, low-contrast, highly transparent, and blurred-boundary smoke regions, containing 6,144 images.

Please organize the data as follows:
